<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-298-560  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 298 560.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 27 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GEnie emerges from European bottle.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Endrijonas, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Electric Information Services Co. (management).andO;Topic:     Information servicesOn-LineGEnie (Information retrieval system)Information Storage and RetrievalGermanyAustriaSwitzerland.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GENIE EMERGES FROM EUROPEAN BOTTLE HANNOVER, WEST GERMANY, 1990 MAR 23 (NB)-- General Electric Information Services, owner and operator of the GEnieteleprocessing network, has announced the availability of the service throughGE Information Services network services distributors in three Europeancountries--Germany, Austria and Switzerland.andM;According to Bill Louden, general manager of the GEnie service, theintroduction of the service became possible when the German PTT (Post,Telephone and Telegraph) changed its regulations 18 months ago.andO;Unfortunately, bureaucratic red tape kept the system from consumer access foralmost two years.andM;&quot;There is a major distinction between a consumer-based e-mail service likeGEnie and a corporate-based service,&quot; said Louden.andP;  &quot;The telecommunicationsindustry has always recognized the corporate need to send e-mail but aprivate citizen in Germany sending mail to a citizen in the US is a differentissue.andP;  There are postal regulations and the PTT doesn't get a piece of it.andO;Those are the regulations that have now been changed, including for e-mail.&quot;andM;Louden added: &quot;We are very pleased to be able to offer local access to theGEnie service in three European countries for the first time.andP;  This new localaccess is being done in response to the many requests we have had from PCenthusiasts.andP;  These three countries are the first step on our European accessprogram.&quot;andM;Louden expects the next country to get full GEnie access will be the UnitedKingdom, within the next three months.andP;  The country after that should be theNetherlands.andP;  Service is also planned for East Germany but there are someproblems to be overcome.andM;Local access to GEnie service in the three countries will be $18 an hour fornon-prime time and $27 an hour for prime time.andP;  The GEnie approach to Europeis unique in another way.andP;  The company is trying to create a one end-userprice for all of Europe.andP;  For the moment, the price is in dollars but in thefuture, Louden says the service might be available in ECUs in the future.andM;(Janet Endrijonas/19900324)</TEXT></DOC>